						               													<description>Swear, will you do the right thing?&amp;#10;Judge a criminal case and make your verdict.&amp;#10;In Intimate Conviction, players play as a group of jurors for an evening or a week. First, they will have to analyse the facts against the accused. Once all the actions of the sworn cards have been completed, the game ends with a final vote where the players will have to decide by a majority whether or not the accused is guilty in a criminal case.&amp;#10;With two or more participants, their opinions will be put to the test more than once as the cards and debates unfold! In the final vote, it is only in the face of their firm conviction that they will have to find the way to victory.&amp;#10;Intime Conviction offers you a unique and entertaining gaming experience that will allow you to simulate the role of jury member in criminal court based on real intrigues. To push the immersion in the closed door further, test the 2-person version and keep the suspense going for 1 week!&amp;#10;Intimate conviction is a craft object entirely designed, manufactured and assembled by hand and in Belgium, by two friends who love stories, cats and fika. &amp;#10;The format of the game is also new: it fits in an envelope.of the game is unusual as well: this game is in an envelope.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;&amp;mdash; description of a distributor.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Two ways to play:&amp;#10;- In group: Play with friends at a party by recreating the closed door ambiance (about 2h game)&amp;#10;- in duo: Make it last by revealing only a few new elements every day.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;How to play (condensed):&amp;#10;Place the crime scene in the middle of the table and give each player a Juror card.&amp;#10;Inspect the crime scene, then read the defendant's deposition. Reveal the Juror cards one by one.&amp;#10;When the Jury is ready to vote, the final vote takes place. If a majority isn't reached, the debate continues until someone switches sides.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;The verdict is announced, a final revelation is unveiled (brand new information is discovered).&amp;#10;You win if you settled on the right decision.&amp;#10;You loose if the verdict was inadequate.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;</description>
